\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 7.       Lagarosiphon}         Harvey
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By J.E. Dandy. 
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Dioecious; stems elongated. Leaves submerged, sessile, linear, with 2 minute nodal scales. Flowers pollinated at the water surface. Spathes tubular, axillary, sessile, the male many flowered, the female 1(-3)-flowered. Sepals and petals subequal. Male flowers breaking free and rising to the surface; stamens 3; staminodes 3. Ovary sessile within the spathe, attenuated into a long, filiform beak; styles 3, 2-fid, free.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Literature: A. A. Obermeyer, {\i Bothalia}{\b  8}: 139-146 (1964).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. L. major} (Ridley) Moss,{\i  Trans. Roy. Soc. S. Afr.}{\b  16}: 193 (1928). Leaves up to 30 × 3 mm, alternate, densely crowded towards the ends of the branches, patent-recurved, minutely denticulate. Sepals and petals pinkish.{\i  Cultivated in aquaria and naturalized in a few ponds, lakes and rivers in W. & C. Europe.} [Br Ga He It.] ({\i S. Africa}.)
